## Flow-Layer Integration Tests

Unit tests that validate library code are necessary but insufficient. Features
that are wired through pipeline flows or application entry points must also have
at least one test verifying the **flow layer** actually uses the new library code
correctly.

**Why this matters:** A feature validated at the library layer may not be wired
through to the actual pipeline that uses it. The bug runs undetected until
runtime.

**Pattern: Flow-layer smoke test**

```python
def test_pipeline_uses_new_feature_when_configured():
    """Verify pipeline passes the new config through to the processor."""
    import ast
    import inspect

    # Option A: Source inspection (no heavy imports needed)
    source = inspect.getsource(create_pipeline)
    tree = ast.parse(source)
    # Verify the parameter appears in the function body

    # Option B: Lightweight integration test
    config = load_config(feature_enabled=True)
    pipeline = create_pipeline(config)
    assert pipeline.feature_enabled is True
```

**When to add flow-layer tests:**
- Feature adds a new config option that flows through pipeline layers
- Feature changes library behavior that pipeline flows consume
- Feature modifies data contracts between libraries and pipelines

